In Cat4k switch, a interface can be configured as L2 or L3.

For L2 interfaces, the HW mac address will be used.
For L3 interfaces, the chassis's mac address will be used.
  This is so that when interface failover occurs, we don't need to re-arp.

The chassis also has a list of IP addresses that were configured in some
interfaces, or as loopback addresses.  You don't need to set up static routes
between these addresses.  Static routes are for subnet that are conected to,
but outside the routers.


For L2 interfaces: 
- All incoming packets are forwarded based on the mac address. 
- For video routine, we set the dest mac address to be the router's.
  As a result, the packet will be forwarded to the CPU port, at which point
  the ACK will take action.

For L3 interfaces:
- If the dest IP of an incoming packet is in the same subnet, then the mac
  address should be that of the connected interface
- If the dest IP of an incoming packet belongs to a different subnet,
  the dest IP address will be examined.
  - if it is one of the IP address of the router, it will be forwarded
    directly by the K2.
  - if not, the routing table will be looked.
  - if not routing rule can be used, the packet will be dropped
    (usually there is no default gateway for a router).


Router requirement: RFC 1812.
